    Better to put numbers in equations or use a global variable?

    15 May 2024, 12:55 PM
    My big code includes pi (3.141...) in many of its equations. Is it better in terms of speed and memory to actually put 3.141 in each equation, or to define a Global variable PI4trig = 4.*ATN(1) and use that in all those equations?

    Also, might that affect the "Cannot access compiler results" error some of us have been finding in very large programs?

    I guess I could run a test, but someone here probably knows the answer plus factors I haven't considered.

    And as a wise man once said, "Pie are round. Cake are squared."

    Sorry.....

    As pi is a constant, I always declare it as such;
    Code:
    #COMPILE EXE
#DIM ALL

MACRO PI = 3.141592653

FUNCTION PBMAIN () AS LONG

PRINT PI

END FUNCTION
    This is equivalent to putting 3.141592653 in each equation.

    From the PowerBASIC Help File: MACRO

    Joe

    Perhaps a FUNCTION or MACRO as:
    Code:
    FUNCTION PI() AS EXTENDED
  FUNCTION= ATN(1)*4
END FUNCTION  
or
MACRO PI =ATN(1)*4
    The function can be implemented as a SLL.

    Note that the help file has this declaration for pi;
    Code:
    ' Useful Macro functions

MACRO Pi = 3.141592653589793##
    That is, they declare it as an Extended-precision floating-point (##) number.

    #6
    15 May 2024, 01:47 PM
    I use...

    Code:
    MACRO Pi = 3.1415926535897932384626433832795##
MACRO PiOver2 = 1.57079632679489662## 'Pi / 2
MACRO DegToRad = 0.017453292519943295769236907684886## 'Pi / 180##
MACRO RadToDeg = 57.29577951308232##
    EXT (## suffix) is the highest resolution floating point PB-32 datatype, with 18 digits, so the ends of those longer strings are cut off at compile time. (When I added those, I was leaving room for possible new datatypes. And it looks cool.)

    If you perform very simple integer-only or floating-point-only math, datatypes are fairly straightforward under the hood of the compiler. But if you mix integers and floats (and at other times) PB has to make descisions at compile-time about which intermediate datatypes to use. Scratchpad variables that you don't see.

    No matter which floating point variable type(s) you use, PB will evaluate the MACRO string at compile-time. EXT simply truncates it at 18 digits, everything else is rounded down to the appropriate precision. A GLOBAL variable would work equally well, as long as it is an EXT. I'd expect a very small difference in speed.

    I do the same as Eric.

    Another advantage of macros is clarity of code. They avoid "magic numbers" and having to work out where a particular value comes from:

    y = x * 6.28318530717958648
    versus
    y = x * TwoPi.

    #9
    15 May 2024, 03:09 PM
    One more thing...

    If there is any "all-constant math", like TwoPi = 2 * 3.14159... or HalfPi = 3.14159.../2, the compiler will usually do the math at compile time, and store only the resulting value. No runtime delay for that part of the math.

    However ATN() is a runtime function, so ATN(1) -- even though it is a fixed value -- isn't evaluated until runtime. You're better off using a MACRO with a pre-calculated (or looked-up) value for ATN(1) than calling the ATN function over and over and over.
